ncompleteArrayField</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">__u8</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">_bitfield_align_1</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">u8</span><span class=\"p\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"p\">],</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">_bitfield_1</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__BindgenBitfieldUnit</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">u8</span><span class=\"p\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"k\">usize</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__mono_tc_offset</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__IncompleteArrayField</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">__u8</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">_bitfield_align_2</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">u8</span><span class=\"p\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"p\">],</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">_bitfield_2</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__BindgenBitfieldUnit</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"kt\">u8</span><span class=\"p\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"k\">usize</span><span class=\"p\">]</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">tc_index</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">alloc_cpu</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">u16_</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_1</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_2__bindgen_ty_1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">priority</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u32</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">skb_iif</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">core</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">ffi</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">c_int</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hash</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u32</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_2</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_2__bindgen_ty_2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_3</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_2__bindgen_ty_3</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">secmark</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u32</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_4</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_2__bindgen_ty_4</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_5</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_2__bindgen_ty_5</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inner_transport_header</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inner_network_header</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inner_mac_header</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">protocol</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__be16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">transport_header</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">network_header</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">mac_header</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">__u16</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>As you can see, <code>sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_2</code> and <code>sk_buff__bindgen_ty_4__bindgen_ty_1 </code> are almost identical.<br>\nI don't know what to do in this situation, since in the original C srtucture there is only one <code>network_header</code> field and it is not aunder some compilation flag, or something else.<br>\nI'd be glad for the tips what to do in this situation, since I couldn't been able to figure out which one is actually correct</p>",
        "id": 493586786,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike",
        "timestamp": 1736861686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, I figured out the problem with the access to the field. But the question with function access and tips about what to do in the situation when bindgen generates 2 fielsds instead of 2 in the C structure. For now I've been able to access the field with the next code:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">nh1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">skb</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_4</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_1</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">as_ref</span><span class=\"p\">().</span><span class=\"n\">network_header</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">nh2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"n\">skb</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">__bindgen_anon_4</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">headers</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">as_ref</span><span class=\"p\">().</span><span class=\"n\">network_header</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>But I don't really know whether this is fine, since at the end of the day I have 2 identical values in the kernel logs </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">nh1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">78</span>\n<span class=\"n\">nh2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">78</span>\n<span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 493614306,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike",
        "timestamp": 1736869598
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>But the question with function access and tips about what to do in the situation when bindgen generates 2 fielsds instead of 2 in the C structure.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think you created the <code>bindgen</code> issue (<a href=\"https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-bindgen/issues/3089\">https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-bindgen/issues/3089</a>) -- please see my reply there: it is inside a <code>struct_group</code> (so I think it is expected, unless you mean something else).</p>",
        "id": 493632075,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1736874781
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>the first one is about the bindgen and <code>__KERNEL__</code> compilation flag (I may be wrong with naming) and the difference in headers : a lot of the needed functionality which I've used in my C module is under the <code>#ifdef __KERNEL__</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmm... We pass <code>-D__KERNEL__</code>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>and some functions are just not available (like <code>ip_hdr</code> fucntion is not available in include header ip.h, but it is available in kernel source ip.h header).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If you mean you are not seeing it in the output, it is a <code>static inline</code>, which is why we have the <code>helpers/</code> for:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Non</span><span class=\"o\">-</span><span class=\"n\">trivial</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">C</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">macros</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">cannot</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">be</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">used</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">in</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Rust</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Similarly</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inlined</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">C</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">functions</span>\n<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">cannot</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">be</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">called</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">either</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">This</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">file</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">explicitly</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">creates</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">functions</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s\">\"helpers\"</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">that</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">wrap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">those</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">so</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">that</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">they</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">can</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">be</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">called</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">from</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Rust</span><span class=\"p\">.</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>You may want to test <a href=\"https://lore.kernel.org/rust-for-linux/20250107035058.818539-1-alistair@alistair23.me/\">https://lore.kernel.org/rust-for-linux/20250107035058.818539-1-alistair@alistair23.me/</a>, by the way.</p>",
        "id": 493632743,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1736875023
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for answering. And yes it was me in Github, I didn't knew about the existance of the <code>struct_group</code>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>it is inside a <code>struct_group</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ok, so I suppose that I have to use this (<code>(*skb).__bindgen_anon_4.headers.as_ref().network_header</code>) to access network_header value. Am I correct on this one?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>which is why we have the <code>helpers/</code> for</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmmm... They were added in v6.12. I had experiments with the v6.9. So, what I am supposed to do? Just patch the kernel to use the helpers as in v6.12 and just add needed functions?</p>",
        "id": 493661742,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike",
        "timestamp": 1736885619
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Am I correct on this one?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think both should work, no? i.e. it is a <code>union</code> of an identical struct. Are you seeing any offset wrong or anything? (I would recommend double-checking the assembly output you get, just in case)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>They were added in v6.12.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>We have had helpers since the very beginning, but previously they were not in the folder but in a single file (<code>helpers.c</code>). If you look for the first commit of the folder, you will see the split.</p>\n<p>In any case, please note that v6.9 is not supported by upstream. For development, you should upgrade to mainline.</p>",
        "id": 493662577,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1736885903
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, if I want to develop a kernel module for an older kernel versions, I have no options except use the newest (supported by upstream) version and hope that everything will be fine and all of the symbols will be found?</p>",
        "id": 493798239,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike",
        "timestamp": 1736926356
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am not sure what you mean -- you can use/develop against old versions on your own (as long as you respect the license etc.). It is just that older kernel versions (apart from the stable ones) are not supported, so you cannot upstream code or get bugs fixed.</p>\n<p>But if what you are asking is whether you can rely on APIs to remain as-is, then: internal kernel APIs are not stable (this applies to all the kernel, not just Rust APIs), please read <a href=\"https://docs.kernel.org/process/stable-api-nonsense.html\">https://docs.kernel.org/process/stable-api-nonsense.html</a></p>\n<p>I hope that helps.</p>",
        "id": 493814115,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1736932413
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, this absolutely helps. <br>\nThanks for answering. And big thanks for sharing the resources and articles. I am a new delevoper in the Linux kernel and I appreciate this.  <br>\nIf you can share some must to read articles, or something similar (for both the Linux kernel and Rust for Linux). For now, I've read only The Linux Kernel Module Programming Guide and a bit from the Rust for Linux page. I'd be very grateful.</p>",
        "id": 493817058,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike",
        "timestamp": 1736933330
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"813840\">Mike</span> has marked this topic as resolved.</p>",
        "id": 493817992,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1736933616
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You're welcome!</p>\n<p>I would recommend reading the <code>Documentation/process/</code> docs and subscribing to the mailing lists you are interested in and so on. For Rust, <code>Documentation/rust/</code> plus checking <a href=\"https://rust-for-linux.com\">https://rust-for-linux.com</a> (it has a lot of links to other resources, too).</p>\n<p>I hope that helps!</p>",
        "id": 493820489,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1736934383
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(In particular, <a href=\"https://docs.kernel.org/process/kernel-docs.html\">https://docs.kernel.org/process/kernel-docs.html</a> has pointers to other resources, and nowadays there is a section on Rust ones too)</p>",
        "id": 493820752,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1736934471
    }
]